\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\size normal
We conclude with a discrete quantum theory version of Bell's theorem, showing
 that non-locality persists in the discrete theory, and no hidden variable
 theories are consistent with our modal-logic-valued operations.
 We exploit methods such as those of Greenberger, Horne, and Zeilinger
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GHZ1990"

\end_inset

 that do not rely on inequalities, and so allow us to escape the disadvantages
 of lack of orderability of discrete field values (see, e.g, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MerminPRL1990,peres1995quantum"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\size normal
First, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{O}_{p^{2}}^{d}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all observables for 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{p^{2}}^{d}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\left(\mathcal{O}\right)$
\end_inset

 be the set of eigenvalues of an observable
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, the Born rule in DQT(I) 
\begin_inset Formula $\dpr$
\end_inset

 asserts that given 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}\in\ffzd{p^{2}}$
\end_inset

 and an observable
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\in\mathbb{O}_{p^{2}}^{d}$
\end_inset

 whether a eigenvalue
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\Delta\left(\mathcal{O}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a possible measurement result or not.
 Hence, a hidden variable theories consistent with 
\begin_inset Formula $\dpr$
\end_inset

 can be described by a function
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 giving directly the measurement result
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=w(\ket{\Psi},\mathcal{O})$
\end_inset

 and satisfying condition (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:consistent"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 & \bullet & \textrm{For any }\ket{\Psi}\in\ffzd{p^{2}}\textrm{, }\mathcal{O}\in\mathbb{O}_{p^{2}}^{d}\textrm{, }\nonumber \\
 &  & w(\ket{\Psi},\mathcal{O})\in\Delta\left(\mathcal{O}\right)\textrm{. Moreover, }\nonumber \\
 &  & \textrm{if }\mathcal{H}\textrm{ is an eigenspace of }\mathcal{O}\textrm{ corresponding to }w\left(\ket{\Psi},\mathcal{O}\right)\textrm{, }\nonumber \\
 &  & \textrm{then }\dpr\left(\ket{\Psi},\mathcal{H}\right)=\textrm{possible .}\label{eq:consistent}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\size normal
Second, local observables 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}''$
\end_inset

 are represented by the observables in subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{O}_{p^{2}}^{d'}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{O}_{p^{2}}^{d''}$
\end_inset

 and be considered as observables in the whole space by applying tensor
 product, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}'\otimes Id_{d''}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Id_{d'}\otimes\mathcal{O}''$
\end_inset

.
 Then, condition (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:locality"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 & \bullet & \textrm{For any }d',d''\in\N\textrm{, }d=d'd''\textrm{, }\mathcal{O}'\in\mathbb{O}_{p^{2}}^{d'}\textrm{, }\mathcal{O}''\in\mathbb{O}_{p^{2}}^{d''}\textrm{. }\nonumber \\
 &  & \textrm{If }\mathcal{H}'\textrm{ is an eigenspace of }\mathcal{O}'\otimes Id_{d''}\textrm{, }\nonumber \\
 &  & \textrm{and }\mathcal{H}''\textrm{ is an eigenspace of }Id_{d'}\otimes\mathcal{O}''\textrm{, }\nonumber \\
 &  & \textrm{and }\dpr\left(\ket{\Psi},\mathcal{H}'\right)=\textrm{possible ,}\nonumber \\
 &  & \textrm{then }w\left(\ket{\Psi},\mathcal{H}''\right)=w\left(\hat{P}_{\mathcal{H}'}\ket{\Psi},\mathcal{H}''\right)\textrm{. }\label{eq:locality}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

represents locality because we require the measurement result of 
\begin_inset Formula $Id_{d'}\otimes\mathcal{O}''$
\end_inset

 should be the same no matter whether we apply the other observable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}'\otimes Id_{d''}$
\end_inset

 which may be far away from 
\begin_inset Formula $Id_{d'}\otimes\mathcal{O}''$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

